explain 5b223cd6f4ff0d9f2dfd504df47517bb057daa43 in the paper

The sequence used for prediction of IN/6VRG structure differs between Ember3D and the other algorithms:
Unique sequence groups:
Group 1: AlphaFold2, ESMFold, ESM3-Large, ESM3-Open
  len=163
  seq=MHGQVDCSPGIWQLDCTHLEGKVILVAVHVASGYIEAEVIPAETGQETAYFLLKLAGRWPVKTVHTDNGSNFTSTTVKAACDWAGIKQEDGIPYNPQSQGVIESMNKELKKIIGQVRDQAEHLKTAVQMAVFIHNKKRKGGIGGYSAGERIVDIIATDIQTKE
Group 2: Ember3D
  len=212
  seq=FLDGIDKAQEEHEKYHSNWRAMASDFNLPPVVAKEIVASCDKCQLKGEAMHGQVDCSPGIWQLDCTHLEGKVILVAVHVASGYIEAEVIPAETGQETAYFLLKLAGRWPVKTVHTDNGSNFTSTTVKAACDWAGIKQEDGIPYNPQSQGVIESMNKELKKIIGQVRDQAEHLKTAVQMAVFIHNKKRKGGIGGYSAGERIVDIIATDIQTKE
The non-Ember predictors do not all use exactly the same sequence, but they all start from the shorter core beginning with: MHGQVDCSPGI...
Ember3D is the outlier, using the full-length sequence beginning with: FLDGIDKAQ...
Meanwhile the SEQRES and ATOM records in the reference PDB file used for IN/6VRG, which are used to create the alignment, contain the longer sequences.
Because the motif is calculated from the alignment, this causes the core logic to abort on 6VRG for non-Ember3D predictions since the motif is not found in the shorter sequences.
